fields.title: Food Network Software Welcome
fields.content:
Welcome to the Food Network Software demonstration site

It's about free open-source software for local food networks: groups of farmers who pool and distribute their food to groups of customers.

It helps customers to order and pay, distributors to deliver, producers, distributors and processors to get paid, and network administrators to coordinate everything.

Food Network Software features in detail

The software was designed by and for several food networks in Wisconsin and Minnesota. Learn more...
It provides features that you cannot get from any other software.
For example:

  • Distributed inventory showing all available products anywhere in the network: in the field, on the farm, at the processor, at the distributor, in a warehouse.
  • Full lot traceability from customer back to the original producer and field. For meat, to the original animal.
  • Pre-season planning, including supply and demand balancing and income projections, for the network as a whole, and for each producer individually.
  • Supports food processing through many steps, including tracing output lots back to input lots all the way back to the original source.
  • Supports culling and packing operations
  • Supports different legal forms such as farmer cooperative, multi-stakeholder cooperative and LLC.

If you have login credentials, you may login to the demo. If you would like login credentials, or have questions, please send us an email.

Frequently Asked Questions

fields.title: Food Network Software Availability
fields.content:
Feature List next

Availability

Producers may enter their own availability, or the administrators can do it for them. This page shows the administators entering availability.

Administrators can also send fresh list emails to customers, and "specials" and what's available will also appear on the customer app.

The distributed or networked inventory tracks products from the field on the farm, through processing and distribution, to the end customer. And back, providing full lot traceability.

fields.title: Customer Help
fields.content:
Back to dashboard

Ordering

Click the Order tab.

You may place new orders, using one of your Product Lists, or a list of all products that will be available from Fifth Season on the order delivery date.

When you enter a new order, click the Save button and you will get a chance to change the order some more or submit it to Fifth Season. You may also leave the order in an unsubmitted state and come back to it later.

You may also pay submitted orders with a credit card using PayPal, which is a secure payment service. You do not need a PayPal account to do so.

You will also see lists of your unsubmitted orders, changeable orders, and recently submitted orders that are no longer changeable.

You may also delete unsubmitted or changeable orders.

Product Lists

Click the Product Lists tab/

Product Lists are templates for new orders. If you place a new order using a product list, you will see only products from that list.

You may create as many product lists as you like. You may also change your existing product lists, adding or removing products.

Invoices

Click the Invoices tab.

You will see a list of your unpaid invoices, and can pay them with a credit card if you wish.

You can also see your past invoices from any date range.

History

Click the History tab.

By selecting a date range, you will see a table summarizing your purchases by product for that timespan.

Plans

Click the Plans tab.

You may enter your expected purchase quantities for a selected date range, either using your combined product lists, or all products. By doing so, you will help the Food Network balance their supply and demand, and the administrator will thank you.

fields.title: Frequently Asked Questions
fields.content:
What's the difference between a food network and a food hub?

"Food hub" has become a popular meme lately, promoted by the USDA.

The USDA's working definition of a regional food hub is "A centrally located facility with a business management structure facilitating the aggregation, storage, processing, distribution, and/or marketing of locally/regionally produced food products". You can read more about their ideas here.

So a food hub is primarily a facility. It might or might not have a food network associated with it. It might serve more than one food network.

A food network is primarily about the relationships between the participants. A food network is at least a group of associated producers who have a staff that administers the aggregation and distribution of their food products. They may or may not have a food hub facility.

This software will be useful to food hubs as well as food networks. But the planning features will be most useful to a food network with strong relationships between the customers as well as the producers. And the processing features will be most useful to a food network that also has a food processing facility.

How can I get this software for my food network? And how much will it cost?

The software itself is free. You can download it from here.

However, there are two catches:

  1. The software runs on a Web server. If you don't know how to run one, you can rent one for less than $10 per month. We recommend WebFaction.
  2. Setting it up requires some skill. You can do it yourself, or hire a programmer, or we can do it for you. You can pay us $50 per hour, or we will work for equity, which means you don't need to pay us now.

We want to have the software be pre-hosted, called "Software as a service" or SAAS, so new groups could get up and running quickly without so much help. That will take more money, or more volunteer technical help, than we have at this stage.

Who are the food networks that helped to design this software?
  • The Southeast Minnesota Food Network of Elgin, MN.
  • The Producers and Buyers Co-op of Elk Mound WI.
  • Fifth Season Cooperative of Viroqua WI.
  • Keewaydin Organics of Viroqua WI.

You can learn more about these food networks and the history of this software here.

If you have other questions, please send us an email.

fields.title: Food Network Software Features
fields.content:
This a list of Food Network Software features, with links to details.

You may also follow a sequential tour of the features.

Applications

  • Distribution: This is the main operational app for the Food Network administrators. It is the only app that we have included in the feature details at this time. (More to come...)
  • Customer: This app allows customers to enter and manage their own orders, invoices and payments.
  • Producer: This app allows producers to enter their own plans, availability and process information.

Distribution Cycle

Distribution allows multiple delivery cycles per week, with different delivery days, routes, order closing times, and customers.

Availability

The network gets information on what's available from producers. Either the producers themselves, or the network administrators enter the information in the software's distributed inventory system.

Distributed or networked inventory is different from the usual inventory systems. It means that the network keeps track of inventory in many places that it does not hold or own. It could be on the farms, at processors, at distribution warehouses, or delivered to customers.

Details...

Processing

The software tracks and manages food processing of one or many steps. For example, slaughter and cut beef, or cull, grade, slice and freeze vegetables. It will track processed meat back to the source animal.

Details...

Orders

The software allows customers to place their own orders, or the network administration to enter orders from customers over the phone or via email.

Details...

Invoices

The software allows customers to view and pay their invoices online, or the administrators can email or print and mail invoices to the customers.

Details...

Payments

The software figures out how much money is due from customers and how much money is due to producers, processors and distributors.

Details...

Planning

The software handles pre-season planning, including production planning for producers and processors, demand planning for customers, supply and demand balancing, and planned income for the network as well as for each producer.

Details...

fields.title: Food Distribution Help
fields.content:
Back to operational dashboard

Getting started

The Distribution system has two main sections: Admin and the weekly Operational tabs. Use Admin for initial setup of master data, and flexible viewing or correcting of operational details. Use the Operational tabs for the regular weekly operations cycle, and an easier way to enter product plans.

Use Admin to create the following master information:

  • Food Network
  • Producers
  • Products

    • Products have a number of settings, which you can read about here.

    When you add a product, at the bottom of the page, you can also say which producers provide that product.

  • Delivery Cycles

    • If a network has more than one delivery date per week, you may want to use Delivery Cycles. They define the delivery day and order closing time, and you can associate customers with one or more delivery cycles on the bottom of either the delivery cycle or customer page.

  • Customers

    • At the bottom of the page for adding or changing a customer, you can also add more contacts for the customer. Those contacts may have online users associated with them.

  • Customer Contact Online Users

    • Customers have their own section of the system for ordering. A customer who wants to manage their own orders online will need a system user, which will need to be created by a superuser. Customer Contact Online Users associate system users with the customer they work for. When a user associated with a Customer logs into the system, they will automatically be redirected to the Customer section of the system, where they can see their own help page.

    Producers can also have their own section of the system, and Producer Contacts can associate system users with the producer they work for. Logging in as a Producer works like Customers. Producers can enter their own availability and plans, and manage their own processes.

  • Processors
  • Distributors
  • Process Types

    • These specify different types of food processing, for example, meat slaughtering and cutting, or making frozen pizza.

  • Service Types

    • These specify different types of services, for example, food processing services or transportation.

Pre-season (or any time): enter plans for producers

Plans are entered by producer, product and date range. Plans ideally would be entered based on last year's demand, maybe adjusted by a growth factor.

Which producers and products appear in the Availability and Process forms for a given date is determined either by Producer-Product relationships, entered when you enter Products, or by Production Plans. If the Producer has either some related Products or Production Plans, they will appear in the Availability selection list. Once you select a producer, if the producer has a production plan, only products that are planned for the availability date will appear. If no product plan, all products related to the producer will appear.

You can use the Plan tab to enter plans for one date range per product for a producer (for example, for the whole season). If you want many date ranges per product for a producer, use Product Plans in Admin.

Weekly operation cycle

  1. Enter what's available this week

    2. Use the Avail tab to enter what's available from producers, either on the farm or somewhere else. Each availability row shows two quantities: Ready and Received. Ready means ready for pickup. Received means received into warehouse inventory. The Custodian field refers to who has the goods other than the Producer. Could be a Processor or a Distributor, and the goods might in the distributor's warehouse and so do not need to be picked up.

    Use the Process tab to enter food that is being processed this week, and is now ready to be ordered. This food will usually be held at the Processor's.

    The system keeps track of available quantities by deleting deliveries.

    Expiration: Lots of available product expire (no longer are available) after their expiration date. The expiration date is set automatically when the lot is created, by adding the product's expiration days to the lot's creation date. The default expiration is 6 days. In other words, lots will become unavailable next week. If you want all lots of a product to be available for longer, change the expiration days for that product, and new lots will be available longer (but existing lots will not be changed). If you want a particular lot or lots to be available longer, go into Admin and change the expiration date on the lot (Inventory Item).

  2. Send Fresh List emails to customers

    3. This feature is temporarily disabled for redesign.

  3. Enter orders

    4. Orders may be entered by customers using their own section of the system, or network staff may enter orders through the Order tab. The form shows all available inventory items from all producers, and you enter the quantities of each item that the current customer wants to order. You can also override unit prices, and enter notes about customer special requests.

  4. Fill and ship orders

    5. Staff prints out the Order Table for the delivery crew (from the Orders tab). The delivery crew marks it up to show which producer's food will go to which customers.

    Staff then enters the delivery info using the Update Lots tab. Sometimes filling one customer order item requires food from several producers. Update Lots accomodates this requirement.

  5. Manage shorts

    6. Use the Orders tab to view shorts, change short orders, and short notice emails to customers..

  6. Send order emails to customers

    7. This feature is temporarily disabled for redesign.

  7. Print invoices

    8. Use the Invoice tab to print invoices for each customer order. The printed invoices may be delivered with the order.

  8. Enter payments from customers

    9. Payments from customers can (eventually) enter the system three ways:

    1. The customer pays invoices online with a credit card,
    2. you enter customer payments and associate them with orders,
    3. you just mark orders "paid".

    Only the third method is implemented now.

    You can mark orders "paid" through the Order tab, or Orders in Admin.

  9. Compute payments to producers, processors and distributors

    10. The Network pays producers etc. after the customer pays the order. The Producer Payments tab tells how much money is due to which producers, and Payment Update computes and enters the payments that will be paid out this week.

    When payments are due: If the Product or Service Type is marked "pay on terms", then the member is paid on the Food Network's member terms. If not, the member payment is due when the customer pays for the order.

  10. Print statements for producers, processors and distributors

    11. The Statements tab generates printable statements to accompany payments. Enter a date range, and statements will be generated for all payments within the range. Note: the payments must be entered using Payment Update before the statements will appear.

fields.title: Food Network Software History
fields.content:
This software was designed by and for a group of food networks. Here's how it happened:

  1. The Southeast Minnesota Food Network was our first group, in spring 2008. Pam Benike, the SMFN administrator, had managed that network for several years and knew exactly what she wanted in a computer system. She set the basic pattern for the software,

    2. SMFN is a Limited Liability Company (LLC). They have been so successful that they have created their own warehouse and distribution center, and have their own refrigerated truck.



  2. The Producers and Buyers Co-op of Elk Mound WI was our second network, in spring 2009. Sherrie Beyer of River Country RC&D and Pam Herdrich of the USDA helped to design a bunch of changes for this version. Shawn McMartin, Justin Kemp and Linda Luberda suggested more improvements a year later.


    3. PBC differs from SMFN in several ways, for example: PBC is a multi-stakeholder cooperative, where the producers, buyers and distributors are all members of the co-op. PBC uses an outside distributor, whereas SMFN does their own distribution. PBC also orders by lot: that is, customers order specific lots of food from specific producers, whereas SMFN customers order by product and SMFN assigns lots to orders when they load their truck.

  3. Fifth Season Cooperative of Viroqua WI is our third network, just getting started now. Nicole Penick, their administrator, is helping to design a new set of software changes for Fifth Season.

    4. Fifth Season, like PBC, is a multi-stakeholder cooperative, but they add processors and co-op workers as members. Their buyers will enter their own orders, unlike SMFN and PBC where the network staff enters the orders while talking to the buyers on the phone. And the buyers may pay for their orders with credit cards, which SMFN and PBC did not offer. Fifth Season producers will also enter their own availability and planning information.

  4. Keewaydin Organics is our fourth network. They are another LLC, like SMFN. Keewaydin has been operating for several years, although they are just getting started with the Food Network Software.

    5. Rufus Hauke and Josh Staum are helping to design some software changes for Keewaydin. Their additional features include handling of short orders and multiple delivery days with different delivery schedules.

fields.title: Food Network Software Invoices
fields.content:
Feature List

previous next

Invoices

Customers can see their own invoices online. The administrators see all invoices.

The administrators can email, or print and mail, invoices to customers.

fields.title: Food Network Software Orders
fields.content:
Feature List

previous next

Orders

Customers can enter their own orders, or the administrators can do it for them. Here we see the administrator order entry procedure.

The order form shows all available products. The administrator form allows over-ordering, because the network can often get more products if they have more demand. The customer order form does not allow over-ordering.

The software manages shorts, notifying both the customer and administrators when the network cannot completely fill orders. This page would allow the administrators to allocate the available supply among all the customer orders. (In this case, there is only one.)

The software can automatically send short change emails to customers.

fields.title: Food Network Software Payments
fields.content:
Feature List

previous next

Payments

The Payment Table shows all payments due to producers, processors and distributors, in detail.

Administrators can select transactions to be paid.

The software also presents statements to producers, processors and distributors showing their payments with all of the transactions that are covered by the payment.

fields.title: Food Network Software Planning
fields.content:
previous Feature List

Planning

The planning features include individual plans for producers and customers, and two tables that combine all of the plans to balance supply and demand and forecast planned income.

Producers, processors and customers can enter their own plans, or the administrators can do it for them.

The Supply vs Demand table combines all of the plans from producers, processors and customers and shows the balance of supply minus demand for each product for each week in any selected time period.

The Planned Income table shows the expected gross and net income from suppliable demand: that is, the amount of planned customer demand that the network can supply from the plans of producers and processors.

You can drill down into any weekly column of the Supply and Demand or Planned Income tables to see the details of each producer, processor and customer's plans for that week.

fields.title: Food Network Software Processing
fields.content:
Feature List

previous next

Processing

You can track and manage food processing of any complexity. Here we see beef processing steps...

...and here we see culling and grading vegetables. The number two's will go on into a slicing operation, and from there maybe to freezing or some other process.

fields.title: Food Network Software Producer Help
fields.content:
Back to dashboard

Entering Available Products

Click the Avail tab.

Availability is for products that are ready for sale as-is, on the farm or elsewhere. If a product needs processing before it is ready for sale, use the Process tab.

In both Availability and Prcesses, you will see a field called Custodian. That means, somebody else who now has custody of the product, rather than the original producer. You may select the original producer as the custodian, but it is not necessary.

You may enter available lots for any product on your plans for the availability date. See Planning below.

Processed Products

Click the Process tab.

You may start a new Process using any of the Process Types in the dropdown list. At this time, new Process Types must be created by Food Network administrators. Ask them if you don't see the Process Type that you want, of the Process Type does not allow the number and types of entries you need.

Processes take input lots and change them into different output lots. For example, a culling or grading process might take unculled produce and separate it into #1's, #2's, etc. A slaughtering and cutting process might take a live animal, slaughter it, and cut it into sellable pieces.

Some processes require available lots of their input products. Others can start with nothing, and enter the input lots while entering the rest of the process information.

You will also see a list of your processes for the current week. If the outputs from a process have not been used, you may delete a process. (Once you have submitted a process to the system, you cannot change it; you can only delete it and start over.)

Planning

Click the Plans tab.

You may enter your expected production quantities for a selected date range. Once you have entered a production plan, you can then use your previously planned products to change or extend that plan, or select "All Products" to add more products to your existing plan.

Also, once you have entered your own plan, you will be able to see the Supply vs Demand and Projected Income tables.

The Supply vs Demand table combines your production plans with production plans for other producers and also demand plans from Network customers. You can see where the Network will have more supply than demand, and where it will have more demand than supply. You might want to change your own production plans accordingly.

The Projected Income table shows your potential income, based on the amount of your production plans that the Network's customers have plans to buy. This is not a guarantee of income, because customer plans may not correspond to their actual orders, and other Network producers may supply some of the demand. If you want to see the details of supply and demand for a week (for example, to see if other producers plan to supplying some of the demand), click the date on top of the column.

fields.title: Product Settings
fields.content:
Back to operational dashboard   Back to main help page

Product Settings

Parent

Products may have other products for parents. Parent products appear in the Category column in product tables. For example, Hamburger per lb may have a parent Beef, which may have a parent Meat. So you would see Meat, Beef in the Category column for Hamburger per lb.

Typically parent products would not be sellable, plannable or inventoried. In other words, you would not sell plain Meat or Beef, but you might sell Hamburger per lb. The categories are useful to make the product tables more readable, and also they may be used for aggregate reports: for example, how much Meat have we sold so far this year?

Sellable

Does the network sell this product? In other words, should this product appear in Order forms?

Plannable

Should this product appear in Planning forms, and the Supply and Demand and Planned Income tables?

Inventoried

Inventory in Food Network Software is different from most other inventory systems. It is a distributed inventory system, managing items that are owned by other parties. The inventory might be on the farm in the field, at a distributor, at a processor, or in the network's own facility.

The reason for this distributed inventory system is so the network can keep track of what food is available, where it is, and what food from which producers was sent to a particular customer on a particular order.

So this setting asks if this product should be managed by the network's distributed inventory system. Note that the network can sell products that are not inventoried. For example, some products might be available in such large quantities that it does not make sense for the network to keep track of their availability. In this case, availability for ordering is set on the Producer Product association in a field called "Default Available Qty". This field is also used in the Supply and Demand and Planned Income tables.

Pay producer

If checked, the Food Network pays the producer for issues, deliveries and damages of this product.

When would you not want to pay the producer for a product? Usually when the product is processed in some way, and the network pays the producer for the finished product, but not the inputs to the process. For example, in a culling process, the network might pay the producer a different price for number 1's than number 2's, and nothing for rejects. And the network would then not pay for unculled products, because the payments went for the culled products. Or, for beef, the network might pay for hanging weight or cuts, but not for the full weight of the live animal.

Pay producer on terms

If checked, the producer of the product is paid for deliveries to customers on member terms (a number of days, as defined in Food Network settings). If not, producers are paid based on customer order payments: that is, when the customer pays for an order, the producers of products delivered on that order are due to be paid. Note: Issues to processes are always paid on member terms.
